{With a balanced hand and 16 points you open 1NT. In the Bridge dictionary under "Opening 1NT Bid" they probably have a picture of this hand. Partner responds 2NT.  

Partner's 2NT bid is invitational. Specifically it tells you to pass with 15 points or bid 3NT with 17 points. But it doesn't tell you what to do when you have 16 points. So you have to make a judgement about your hand. Is it closer to 15 or closer to 17? The answer is definitely "closer to 17". Aces are actually worth a little more than 4 points and you have three of them. Also, most of your spot cards are higher than average, with only one card below a 7. So you bid 3NT.

East plays 3NT. South leads the \S6, North plays \S2.

<b>East plays 3NT. South leads the \S6, North plays \S2.</b>

Winner count: \S 2 : \H 2 : \D 0 : \C 1 : Total = 5

You are bound to get 2 winners in \Ss. You need to create 4 winners and the \D suit offers the perfect opportunity. Drive out the \DA and the other four \Ds are winners. But there is a very critical problem. If the defenders hold up their \DA until the third round of the suit you may be locked out of dummy.

Suppose you win the first \S with your \S8. Then you start on \Ds and the defense wins the third one and leads a \H. You win the \H but your only hope of reaching dummy is with a \S. If you take your \SA, then lead a low one South will take his \SK and two more. Suppose you try to sneak over to dummy by playing your \ST. South will jump up with \SK, then lead another which you must win with your \SA. No entry.

In hindsight the answer is simple. Win the very first \S trick with your \SA. That leaves dummy with the \S Q J and a sure entry. It seems strange to win a trick with a higher card than necessary but it is the only way to make this contract.

Here are the initial hands.  

This shows the hands after five tricks have been played in the case where you took the first trick with your \S8. You have just won trick 5 with your \HK.

Notice that no matter what you try South can prevent you from reaching dummy.

This shows the hands after five tricks have been played in the case where you took the first trick with your \SA. You have just won trick 5 with your \HK.

Notice that South cannot prevent you from reaching dummy with the \S Q J.}
[Play "W"]S6

